The '''right of redemption''', in the [[law]] of [[real property]], is the right of a debtor whose real property has been foreclosed upon and sold to reclaim that property if they are able to come up with the money to repay the amount of the debt. Most [[U.S. state]]s have a statutory provision that allows such a reclamation of property.
