y.ca/article/1293 |date=2008-03-12 }}, ''[[The Varsity (newspaper)|The Varsity]]'', November 27, 2007</ref> A 2008 article in the ''[[Torontoist]]'' stated that the Church does not have status as a federally registered charity for tax purposes.<ref>Robin Rix: [http://torontoist.com/2008/02/was_that_a_hate.php "Was that a hate crime?"], ''[[Torontoist]]''</ref> Religious scholars [[Douglas E. Cowan]] and [[David G. Bromley]] stated in a 2006 publication that "Scientology has yet to receive official recognition as a religion in Canada".<ref name="intronew185" /> | [[Scientology in Canada]] |- | [[Chile]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|As of 2009, Scientology is considered a cult.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/Tendencias/2009/07/08/727830/la-fe-detras-del-actor.html |title=La fe del detrás del actor |publisher=[[El Mercurio]] |date=July 8, 2009|language=Spanish}}</ref> | |- | [[China]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|China as of yet has refused to legitimize Scientology.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} |- | [[Colombia]] | {{no2}} Scientology was a recognized as a religion in Colombia on May 2017. An "ideal church" was opened in Bogota, Colombia in 2015.<ref>http://www.latimes.com/opinion/readersreact/la-ol-scientology-tax-exempt-20180201-story.html</ref> |- | [[Costa Rica]] | {{no2}} Scientology was recognized as a religion in Costa Rica in 1991.<ref>https://news.co.cr/scientology-costa-rica/1572/</ref> |- | [[Croatia]] | {{no2}}Croatia recognizes Scientology as a religion since 22 December 2003<ref name="Monde">[http://www.lemonde.fr/cgi-bin/ACHATS/acheter.cgi?offre=ARCHIVES&type_item=ART_ARCH_30J&objet_id=1019433 La justice espagnole accorde à la Scientologie le statut de religion], ''Le Monde'', 2008-01-09</ref><ref>[http://www.appluprava.hr/RegistarVjerskihZajednica/faces/WEB-INF/pages/searchResult.jsp SCIJENTOLOŠKA CRKVA U HRVATSKOJ, appluprava.hr]</ref> | |- | [[Czech Republic]] |style="background: #ABCDEF;"|Not registered as a religion (it is not recorded in the register of churches and religious societies).<ref>https://www.mkcr.cz/directory-of-churches-and-religious-societies-and-associations-of-churches-and-religious-societies-940.html?lang=en</ref> Dianetic centers are registered as associations. | |- | [[Denmark]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|In Denmark the Church of Scientology is not officially approved as a religion. It first applied for approval in the early 1970s; two further unsuccessful applications followed in 1976 and 1982. In mid-1997, the Church of Scientology filed a fourth application, which was suspended at their own request in 2000. In suspending their application, the Church asked the Ministry of Ecclesiastical Affairs to clarify the approval procedure, but was told that it must first submit an application before any feedback could be provided. Despite Scientology's unofficial status, the Church of Scientology maintains its European headquarters in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=USSDenmark>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2007/90172.htm U.S. Department of State – 2007 Report on International Religious Freedom: Denmark]</ref> | |- | [[Finland]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|Scientology is not officially recognized as a religion. An application by the Church of Scientology to be registered as a religious body was denied by the Ministry of Education in 1998 on the grounds that "the known nature of the activities is not public worship in the sense meant by the law on freedom of religion". The denial was issued after the Church "had failed to comply with a request for more information".<ref>http://www.helsinki.fi/~huuskone/Scn/opm-hylk.html{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> | |- | [[France]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|Since 1995, Scientology has sometimes been classified as a ''secte'' (cult), for instance in a report of the [[National Assembly of France]].<ref>[http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/rap-enq/r2468.asp National Assembly of France report No. 2468]</ref> On this basis, a hostile stance is generally taken against the organization.<ref name = tribunalvic>[http://www.prevensectes.com/lyon2.htm Appel du Jugement du Tribunal de Grande Instance de Lyon (Affaire : Patrick Vic)] (in French). Tribunal's decision. 28 July 1997.</ref> In 2009, Scientology was fined the equivalent of almost US$900,000 upon conviction for fraud.<ref>''Time'' magazine, 9 November 2009 p. 10</ref> | [[Scientology in France]] |- | [[Germany]] | {{depends|The status of Scientology in [[Germany]] is unresolved. Two points are contested: firstly, whether or not the teachings of Scientology qualify as a religious or ideological teaching, and secondly, whether or not these teachings are only used as a pretext for purely commercial activity; if the latter were the case, this would most likely imply that Scientology would not qualify for protection as a religious or ideological community under Article 4 of the [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany|German constitution]].<ref name="BundestagRFRW">[http://www.bundestag.de/dokumente/analysen/2007/Rechtliche_Fragen_zu_Religions-_und_Weltanschauungsgemeinschaften.pdf bundestag.de: Legal questions concerning religious and ideological communities] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125055319/http://www.bundestag.de/dokumente/analysen/2007/Rechtliche_Fragen_zu_Religions-_und_Weltanschauungsgemeinschaften.pdf |date=2011-01-25 }}, prepared by the Scientific Services staff of the German Parliament {{Link language|de}}<!--German--></ref>}} | [[Scientology in Germany]] |- | [[Greece]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|In the case ''Attiki Prefecture vs KEPHE'', the practice of Scientology was ordered ended in [[Greece]].<ref>''Attiki Prefecture vs KEPHE'', Case Number 7380/1996, Athenian Court of First Instance</ref> An appeal to the Athenian Court of Appeals ended with a reaffirmation of the verdict.<ref>Appeal for ''Attaki Prefecture vs KEPHE'', Case Number 10493/1997, Athenian Court of Appeal</ref> The verdict was originally issued on December 20, 1995, but was not immediately put into effect. In January 1998 a Greek appeals court ordered Scientology's assets liquidated.<ref name="criticsabroad">{{cite web |first=Lucy |last=Morgan |title=Abroad: Critics public and private keep pressure on Scientology |url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/32999/Worldandnation/Abroad__Critics_publi.html |work= |publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=1999-03-29 |accessdate=2007-11-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yLc3T9Xn?url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/32999/Worldandnation/Abroad__Critics_publi.html |archivedate=2011-05-01 |df= }}</ref>
According to the U.S. Department of State, Scientologists, who are mostly located in the [[Athens]] area, practice their faith through a registered non-profit civil-law organization.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2003/24411.htm "Greece: International Religious Freedom Report 2003"]. [[U.S. Department of State]]. 2003</ref> Two laws from the 1930s require recognized or "known" religious groups wanting to open houses of worship to obtain "house of prayer" permits from the Ministry of Education and Religion. There is no formal mechanism in Greece to gain recognition as a known religion. By law, the Ministry may base its decision to issue permits on the opinion of the local [[Greek Orthodox Church|Orthodox]] [[bishop]]; documentation provided to the Department of State by Scientology representatives and the Greek Orthodox Church indicated the Ministry did indeed consult with local bishops in some cases. According to Ministry officials, applications for additional houses of prayer were numerous and approved routinely; however, Scientologists in Greece had not been able to register or build a house of prayer.<ref name=USSGreece2004>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2004/35458.htm U.S. Department of State – 2004 Report on International Religious Freedom: Greece]</ref> According to state.gov report of 2017, Scientology groups function as registered nonprofit civil law organizations. The government did not legally recognize weddings conducted by members of those religious groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/religiousfreedom/index.htm?year=2017&dlid=280912#wrapper|title=International Religious Freedom Report for 2017|website=www.state.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref> | |- | [[Indonesia]] | {{no2}}According to ''Freedom of religion and belief: a world report'' (1997), Indonesian government legislation recognizes the "right of all religions to exist and function in society" and "the Church of Scientology has experienced no difficulties in gaining registration".<ref name=boyle>{{Citation | last =Boyle | first =Kevin | last2 =Sheen | first2 =Juliet | title =Freedom of Religion and Belief: A World Report | place = | publisher =Routledge | year =1997 | page = 203 | volume = | edition = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=MFUZkWWgOtMC&pg=PA203&dq=%22Church+of+Scientology+has+experienced+no+difficulties+in+gaining+registration%22&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22Church%20of%20Scientology%20has%20experienced%20no%20difficulties%20in%20gaining%20registration%22&f=false | doi = | id = | isbn =0-415-15977-6 }}.</ref> | |- | [[Israel]] | In January 1987 a parliamentary commission on cults, headed by MK [[Miriam Glazer-Ta'asa]], declared Scientology a cult, although no further measures were taken. Its practice is legal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scientology may be demonized around the world, but in Israel it barely makes waves|url=http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/scientology-may-be-demonized-around-the-world-but-in-israel-it-barely-makes-waves-1.476205|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|agency=Associated Press|date=8 November 2012}}</ref> | |- | [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|In Ireland, the Church of Scientology has not been successful in its attempts to obtain tax-free, charitable status.<ref>Tom Lyons. "[http://www.independent.ie/national-news/troubled-scientology-church-in-ireland-is-now-1m-in-red-95169.html Troubled Scientology Church in Ireland is now €1m in red]", ''[[The Irish Independent]]'', 28 June 2006</ref> | |- | [[Italy]] | {{no2}} In terms of corporate status, the Italian Church of Scientology is one of Italy's non-profit and common-law associations; it has neither an ''intesa'' (recognition agreement with the Italian state), nor is it a recognized confessional community (''ente di culto'').<ref>[http://www.hrwf.net/religiousfreedom/news/2005pdf/italy_2005.pdf Categorizsation of Religions in Italy]</ref>
Some courts, including those in Rome and Turin, have viewed Scientology as a religion, although the Appeals Court of Milan did not do so during the 20-year-long criminal trial of various Scientologists.<ref>"[http://www.cesnur.org/testi/scient_oct2000.htm Scientology Wins Mother of All Court Cases]"</ref> After it twice refused to recognize Scientology as a religion, its decisions were overturned by the Italian Supreme Court.<ref>[http://www.cesnur.org/testi/SCIE.HTM The Italian Supreme Court Decision on Scientology]</ref> The Italian Supreme Court gave exact guidelines to the Appeals Court of Milan to follow.<ref name="Decision">[http://www.cesnur.org/2001/scient_01_en.htm The Court of Appeals of Milan Decision]</ref> Following these guidelines the Appeals Court exonerated the defendants of all charges.<ref name="Decision"/> The Italian Supreme Court issued a decision fully recognizing Scientology as a religion on October 9, 1997.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Is Scientology a Religion? |journal=The Journal of CESNUR |year=2018 |last=Berzano |first=Luigi |volume=2 |issue=2 |issn=2532-2990 }}</ref> In March 2000, the Italian Supreme Court upheld Scientology's religious status in Italy while reaffirming that [[Narconon]] is a non-tax-exempt for-profit business.<ref name=Censur.org/> | |- |[[Japan]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|The first Church of Scientology was opened in 2015 in [[Tokyo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldreligionnews.com/religion-news/scientology/first-japanese-church-of-scientology-ideal-org-opens-in-tokyo|title=First Japanese Church of Scientology 'Ideal Org' Opens in Tokyo, Japan - World Religion News|date=2015-08-11|work=World Religion News|access-date=2018-09-27|language=en-US}}</ref> However, Japan does not officially recognize Scientology as a religion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nipponnews.photoshelter.com/image/I0000dJ9KLc6QnbA|title=The Church of Scientology in Tokyo {{!}} Nippon News|website=nipponnews.photoshelter.com|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> | |- | [[Kazakhstan]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|According to the [[U.S. State Department]]'s 2008 International Religious Freedom Report, Scientologists are among many minority groups facing increasingly negative media coverage in Kazakhstan. During a press conference on April 10, 2008, a spokesperson for the Kazakh government's Procurator General's Office claimed that there were approximately 1,870 religious organizations in the country that presented a threat to national security and were engaged in destructive operations, citing Scientologists as one of the examples (these statements were later removed from the press conference transcript posted on the PGO website).<ref name=USKAZ>[http://kazakhstan.usembassy.gov/irf-2008.html U.S. Department of State – 2008 Report on International Religious Freedom: Kazakhstan]</ref>
In 2008, parliament discussed new draft legislation which would severely restrict religious freedom.<ref name=USKAZ /> In February 2009, [[Interfax]] reported that Kazakh prosecutors were seeking liquidation of the Scientology Church in [[Karaganda]].<ref name=InterfaxKaz>Staff (2009-02-04). "[http://www.interfax-religion.com/?act=news&div=5669 Kazakh prosecutors seeking liquidation of so-called Scientology Church in Karaganda]", ''[[Interfax]]''</ref> In a statement on its website, the Kazakh Prosecutor General's Office cited concerns over national security, as Scientologists' activity was aimed at undermining the "Kazakh nation's health through inflicting harm on people's psychic and physical health", and added that Scientologists were practising medicine outside medical institutions, and without the requisite education.<ref name=InterfaxKaz /> | |- | [[Kyrgyzstan]] | {{no2}}The U.S. Department of State's 2005 Report on International Religious Freedom announced that the Church of Scientology had been registered as a religious group by the Kyrgyzstan State Commission on Religious Affairs.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2005/51562.htm U.S. Department of State – 2005 Report on International Religious Freedom: Kyrgyzstan]</ref> | |- | [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] | {{no2}}In May 2017 Basic Court Skopje II approved the registration of the Church of Scientology of Macedonia, and the Home of Prayer religious group.<ref>http://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/religiousfreedom/index.htm?year=2017&dlid=280932</ref> | |- | [[Mexico]] | {{no2}}The [[Secretaría de Gobernación]] denied its petitions in 1999, 2004 and 2012. In 2017, the Church of Scientology obtained registration as a religious association.<ref name="cesnur.org">http://www.cesnur.org/2018/usc_galindo.htm</ref><ref name="cesnur.org"/> | |- | [[New Zealand]] | {{no2}}The Inland Revenue Department of the government of New Zealand issued an official decision in December 2002 which accepted that the Church of Scientology of New Zealand met the requirements of the definition of Charitable Purpose in s OB 1 of the Income Tax Act 1994. The Inland Revenue Department made no ruling about whether Scientology was a religion or not. In June, 2008 the New Zealand Charities Commission accept the registration of the Church of Scientology as a charity under the category of religious activities. It made no ruling as to whether Scientology was a religion. The New Zealand Charities Commission is currently considering requests for the Church of Scientology to be deregistered as a charity.<ref name=NZH /> | [[Scientology in New Zealand]] |- | [[Netherlands]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"| On 17 October 2013 the Court of Amsterdam determined that Scientology is a charitable organization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/26653/questions-in-netherlands-house-of-representatives-over-scientology-tax-loopholes|title=Questions in Netherlands House of Representatives over Scientology tax loopholes|date=2012-03-17}}</ref> But on December 12, 2014, the Supreme Court annulled the verdict,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uitspraken.rechtspraak.nl/inziendocument?id=ECLI:NL:HR:2014:3565|title=Verdict Supreme Court |date=2014-12-12}}</ref> regarding ''Art. 6.33 Wet IB 2001 en art. 41a Uitv.reg. IB 2001 (tekst 2008)'' {{quote|Religious or spiritual institution is [[Algemeen nut beogende instelling|ANBI]], if the public interest served at least to the same extent as a private interest. Commercial activities are primarily focused on serving a private interest.}} | |- | [[Nicaragua]] | {{no2}} Scientology is recognized as a minority religion in Nicaragua.<ref>https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2001/5681.htm</ref><ref>http://www.patheos.com/library/country-profiles/central-america/nicaragua</ref> |- | [[Norway]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"| Norway does not recognize the official ''Scientologikirken'' (Church of Scientology) as a religious community, but it is registered as a non-profit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=514174|title=Nektes kirkestatus|date=2012-03-17}}</ref> Although it is estimated that around 8000 people have taken scientology-related courses in Norway, the church only has around 100 active members.<ref>http://www.seeto.no/gem/servlet/getGemObject?id=11620{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> ''Scientologikirken'' has a history of settling legal cases out of court, although it was sentenced to refund 600,000 Norwegian kroner worth of course fees to a former member,<ref>{{Cite web|title = scientologi – Store norske leksikon|url = https://snl.no/scientologi|website = Store norske leksikon|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> in addition to the unsuccessful 6-year-long legal battle to grant it official status as a religion.
The church gained controversy in the high-profile case of [[Death of Kaja Ballo|Kaja Ballo's suicide]]. Ballo was the daughter of parliamentary minister [[Olav Gunnar Ballo]].
Norwegians in general regard ''Scientologikirken'' as a cult.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}
As of February 2016, the Church has vacated their offices, and have not released information regarding a new location. Their former offices are to be torn down as part of an urban development and housing project.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} |[[Scientology in Norway]] |- | [[Philippines]] | {{no2}}The Philippines recognizes the Church of Scientology as a religious organization.<ref>{{cite news|last=Crescin|first=Dino|title=Church of Scientology is in the Philippines|url=http://www.philippinesentinel.org/2010/06/church-of-scientology-is-in-the-philippines/|accessdate=10 January 2014|newspaper=The Philippine Tribune|date=5 June 2010}}</ref> | |- | [[Poland]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"| Poland does not officially recognize Scientology as a religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mswia.gov.pl/download/1/25270/E-RejestrHW11022016.pdf|title=List of officially recognized religions in Poland|date=2016-02-11}}</ref> | |- | [[Portugal]] | {{no2}}The Portuguese Government officially recognized Scientology as a religion in November 2007.<ref name=USSPortugal>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100579.htm 2007 U.S. Department of State – 2007 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices: Portugal]</ref> | |- | [[Romania]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"| The Romanian Scientology Church has only 70 members. According to the Law no. 489/2006 Scientology is not included among the 18 officially recognized religions by the State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/scientologia-din-romania-pamant-unguresc-899117.html|title=Scientology in Romania, Hungarian land|date=2010-06-27|language=ro}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lege5.ro/Gratuit/geydamrqgy/legea-nr-489-2006-privind-libertatea-religioasa-si-regimul-general-al-cultelor|title=Legea nr. 489/2006 privind libertatea religioasă şi regimul general al cultelor|date=2007-01-11|language=ro}}</ref> | |- | [[Russia]] | style="background: #ABCDEF;"|The Church has been subjected to considerable pressure from the state in Russia.<ref>[http://www.religionandpolicy.org/show.php?p=1.1.1246 Church of Scientology International Presentation on Religious Freedom in Russia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006233735/http://religionandpolicy.org/show.php?p=1.1.1246 |date=2010-10-06 }}</ref> In April 2007, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled against Russia for repeatedly refusing to consider the Moscow Church of Scientology's application for the status of a legally valid religious association. [[Church of Scientology Moscow versus Russia|The court found]] that the reasons given to deny re-registration of the church by the justice department and endorsed by the Moscow courts had no legal basis.<ref>[http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?action=html&documentId=815108&portal=hbkm&source=externalbydocnumber&table=F69A27FD8FB86142BF01C1166DEA398649 ECHR, ''Church of Scientology Moscow v. Russia'', application no. 18147/02, 5 April 2007]</ref><ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?from=rss_World&set_id=1&click_id=3&art_id=nw20070405161359229C589107 IOL, April 5, 2007]</ref>
In July 2007, the [[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]] City Court ordered that the city's Scientology center be closed for violating its charter by engaging in unlicensed health care services.<ref>{{cite news | author = [[Associated Press]] | title = Russian court shuts down Scientology center in St. Petersburg: prosecutors | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/07/12/europe/EU-GEN-Russia-Scientology.php | publisher = [[International Herald Tribune]] | date = 2007-07-12 | accessdate = 2007-07-16}}</ref> A court in [[Samara, Russia|Samara]] came to a similar decision in November 2008, closing down the activities of the local center for practicing without a license.<ref>{{cite news | last =Staff | title =Hubbard Center closed up in Samara | work =[[Interfax]] | publisher =www.interfax-religion.com | date =November 20, 2008 | url =http://www.interfax-religion.com/?act=news&div=5395 | accessdate =2008-11-20 }}</ref>
In September 2009, the European Court of Human Rights issued a binding ruling in favor of two Scientology branches in [[Surgut]] and [[Nizhnekamsk]], which had been denied registration as "religious organizations". The two organizations were awarded €20,000 in costs and damages. The ruling, which cannot be appealed against, said that Russia could not ban the Church of Scientology simply because it did not have a long history in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iJ_Lp6ZG3jVlOzswrzbOGf08SdkgD9B2BUGG0|title=Scientologists win rights case against Russia|date=2009-10-02|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2009-10-06}}</ref>
In 2010 some of the works of L. Ron Hubbard were included into the [[Federal List of Extremist Materials|Federal List of banned extremist materials]],<ref>[http://palm.newsru.com/religy/30jun2011/genprok.html "В России запрещены за экстремизм книги основателя сайентологии и фантаста Хаббарда"]. palm.newsru.com. 30 июня 2011.</ref> but removed on 3 May 2011.<ref>[http://www.scientologyfacts.ru/?show=news&id=66 "Five dimensions of religion: the example of Scientology"]. Scientology Facts. Retrieved January 15, 2017.</ref> Another such attempt was made by prosecutor in mid-2011 but was unsuccessful.<ref>Ямало-Ненецкий Авт. Окр. (January 7, 2011). [http://www.sova-center.ru/misuse/news/persecution/2011/07/d22014/ "Вступило в силу решение о непризнании экстремистской биографии Рона Хаббарда"]. COBA.</ref>
| [[Scientology in Russia]] |- | [[Scotland]] | {{no2}} The Church of Scientology is authorized to perform marriages in Scotland.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-scientology-idUSBRE9BA0CY20131211</ref> |- | [[Slovenia]] | {{no2}}According to a 2008 ''[[Le Monde]]'' report, Slovenia recognizes Scientology as a religion.<ref name="Monde"/> |- | [[South Africa]] | {{no2}}In 1975, Scientology was recognized as a non-profit organization in [[South Africa]], despite the 1972 report of a formal government Commission of Inquiry that recommended otherwise.<ref>[http://www.neuereligion.de/ENG/Chidester/pageviii.htm Scientology: A Religion in South Africa by David Chidester, University of Cape Town, South Africa]</ref> In April 2000, Scientology ministers were granted the right to perform marriages.<ref name="MARRIAGE"/> In December 2007, South Africa granted a certificate to the Church recognizing it as a "Public Benefit Organisation".<ref>[http://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/sa-church-of-scientology-gets-tax-exemption-1.381415#.UJ1bpeQ3sxB SA Church of Scientology gets tax exemption]</ref> | |- | [[Spain]] | {{no2}}On 31 October 2007 the National Court in Madrid issued a decision recognizing that the National Church of Scientology of [[Spain]] should be entered in the Registry of Religious Entities.<ref name="afpspain">{{cite web |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5h-V0Ui506lPl-r8ImubpdUjFbuYA |title=Spanish court rules Scientology can be listed as a religion |author= |publisher=AFP |date=November 1, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226104617/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5h-V0Ui506lPl-r8ImubpdUjFbuYA |archivedate=December 26, 2007 |df= }}</ref> {{wikinews|National Church of Scientology recognized in Spain}} The administrative tribunal of Madrid's High Court ruled that a 2005 justice ministry decision to scrap Scientology from the register was "against the law".<ref name="afpspain" /> Responding to a petition filed by the church, the ruling said that no documents had been presented in court to demonstrate it was anything other than a religious entity.<ref name="Elpais"> {{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/Audiencia/Nacional/reconoce/Cienciologia/iglesia/elpepusoc/20071101elpepisoc_8/Tes |title=La Audiencia Nacional reconoce a la Cienciología como iglesia |author= |publisher=El Pais |date=November 1, 2007}} {{Link language|es}}<!--Spanish--></ref>
Authorities had earlier declared that the government would not interfere in any way with the activities of the Church of Scientology.<ref>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2006/71409.htm U.S. Department of State – International Religious Freedom Report 2006: Spain]</ref> | |- | [[Sweden]] | {{no2}}On March 13, 2000 Scientology was registered as a "religious community".<ref name="CESNUR"/> | |- | [[Switzerland]] | {{no2}}The Federal Council (Bundesrat) issued a written statement on 25 Nov 1996: "According to their nomenclature and their statutes, the Church of Scientology is viewed as a new religious movement, and is to be treated to the existence of other facts as such. The Federal Court shares this view."
In a final decision the Federal Court (''Bundesgericht'') of 14 Feb 1992 confirmed that the Church of Scientology is pursuing religious purposes and falls under the protection of freedom of faith, conscience and worship.<ref>[http://www.scientology-fakten.ch/de/richtigstellung-von-falschinformationen/religion/49-rechtlicheanerkennungch.html Rechtliche Anerkennung von Scientology in der Schweiz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220201411/http://www.scientology-fakten.ch/de/richtigstellung-von-falschinformationen/religion/49-rechtlicheanerkennungch.html |date=2013-12-20 }}, 28 March 2010.</ref> | |- | [[Taiwan]] | {{no2}}In 2003, the National Ministry of the Interior for Taiwan recognized the Church of Scientology of Taiwan as a charitable religious institution, officially adding it to the rolls of the country's recognized religions. Taiwan has 15 Scientology missions and churches, including the one in Kaohsiung.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2016/07/scientology-in-taiwan/493493/</ref> | |- | [[United Kingdom]] | {{no2}}The Church of Scientology was not classified as a religious institution by the UK government until December 2013.<ref name=NatLawRev>{{cite news| url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/united-kingdom-uk-supreme-court-confirms-scientology-religion | work=The National Law Review | title=United Kingdom (UK) Supreme Court Confirms Scientology Is a Religion | date=2013-12-25}}</ref><ref name=USSUK>[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2007/90206.htm U.S. Department of State – 2007 Report on International Religious Freedom: United Kingdom]</ref> The Church's application for charity status in [[England and Wales]] was rejected in 1999,<ref name=cosfulldoc>{{cite web | url = http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/Library/registration/pdfs/cosfulldoc.pdf|title = Decision of the Charity Commissioners for England and Wales |date = 1999-11-17|publisher = [[Charity Commission]] | accessdate = 2006-07-06 |format=PDF |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060623095446/http://www.charity-commission.gov.uk/Library/registration/pdfs/cosfulldoc.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-06-23}} (PDF)</ref> and the Church has not exercised its right of appeal.<ref name=USSUK /> However, in 2000, the Church of Scientology was exempted from UK [[value added tax]] on the basis that it is a not-for-profit body.<ref>Harry Wallop: [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/main.jhtml?xml=/money/2006/08/11/cntax11.xml Scientology tax victory could cost Revenue millions], [[Daily Telegraph]], 11 Aug. 2006</ref> The [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] has confirmed that Scientology is "an officially recognised religion in the [[Royal Navy]]".<ref name=cosfulldoc /> The UK [[Prison Service]] does not recognize Scientology as a religion, but prisoners who are registered as Scientologists may practice their religion and are given access to a representative of the Church of Scientology if they wish to receive its ministry.<ref name=USSUK /> In a December 2013 decision, the [[UK Supreme Court]] ruled unanimously that a London Church of Scientology chapel was a "place of meeting for religious worship" and should be registered as a place for marriage. This judgement endorsed the Australian High Court decision of 1983 "Of the various attempts made to describe the characteristics of religion, I find most helpful that of Wilson and Deane".<ref>https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2013-0030-judgment.pdf paragraph 57</ref> Under Scots law, Scientology ministers had been authorised to perform marriages in Scotland even prior to the December 2013 Supreme Court decision.<ref name=bbc2013>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-25331754 | work=BBC News | title=Supreme Court judges allow Scientology wedding | date=2013-12-11}}</ref>
The UK government has openly criticized the Church in the past, as documented in 1971 in the [[Foster Report]], but places no restrictions upon its activities. | [[Scientology in the United Kingdom]] |- | [[United States of America]] | {{no2}}Since 1993, the [[Internal Revenue Service]] in the United States has formally recognized Scientology as a religion for tax purposes.<ref name="NYTimes97"/><ref name=IrishTimes>{{cite news| url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/scientology-is-a-bona-fide-religion-1.350986 | work=irish Times | title=Scientology is 'a bona fide religion' | date=2003-03-05}}</ref> | [[Scientology in the United States]] |} {{Update|section|reason=Countries wherein Scientology is recognized just added|date=June 2018}} Scientology is not recognised by any of the other 157 member states of the United Nations at this point.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}
